<HEAD>Vatican Appoints Coadjutor in Dallas, New Auxiliary in California</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II on Tuesday appointed a
coadjutor bishop for Dallas and a new auxiliary bishop for the
diocese in Orange County, Calif.
   The pope appointed Monsignor Charles Victor Grahmann, currently
the bishop in Victoria, Texas, as the coadjutor in Dallas.
   Grahmann, 58, is a native of Hallettsville, Texas. He was
ordained a priest in 1956 and consecrated a bishop on Aug. 20, 1981.
   The pope also named Monsignor Michael P. Driscoll, the current
vicar general of the diocese in Orange County, Calif., as the new
auxiliary bishop in that diocese.
   Driscoll, 50, a native of Long Beach, Calif., was ordained in
Los Angeles in 1965. He has served as a parish priest in the
diocese and later as the director of its social services.
