<FIRST>r f PM-UTC-Thailand     12-19 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UTC-Thailand,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>United Technologies Gives to Thai Charity As It Seeks Engine Order</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Technologies Corp., vying for more
than $100 million in jet-engine orders from Thailand's national
airline, has donated $500,000 to a charity run by the Thai royal
family, a newspaper reported today.
   UTC officials called the donation to typhoon victims
humanitarian and said they often give money to victims of natural
disasters, but some industry experts said the contribution appeared
to be an attempt to curry favor with a potentially big customer,
The Hartford Courant reported in a copyright story.
   ``They didn't give that out of the goodness of their heart,''
said retired Navy Rear Adm. Gene R. LaRocque, director of the
Center for Defense Information, a Washington watchdog group.
   Thai officials in Washington said UTC's contribution to the
typhoon relief fund was the largest they were aware of.
   The contribution was given to Thailand's ambassador to the
United States during a private ceremony Dec. 5 at his Washington
residence, U.S. and Thai government officials and an aide to UTC
consultant Alexander M. Haig Jr. confirmed Monday.
   Haig, former U.S. secretary of state and a former UTC president,
approved UTC's contribution to victims of Typhoon Gay in his role
as head of the corporations Pacific advisory committee.
   The typhoon ravaged southern Thailand in November, killing
nearly 500 people and leaving thousands homeless.
   Sales to Thailand of UTC products, ranging from Pratt &amp; Whitney
engines and Sikorsky helicopters to Otis elevators, have grown
seven-fold in the past five years, to $69.1 million in 1988.
   Last summer, Thai Airways International canceled a $65 million
engine supplier, Fairfield-based General Electric Co., and switched
the order to Pratt &amp; Whitney. The order was for engines on three
Airbus A300 wide-bodied jets.
   Pratt and GE are now competing for as much as $120 million in
Thai Airways engine orders, expected to be announced early next
year. Those engines would power at least six A300s and one Boeing
747 being added to the airline's fleet.
   UTC spokesman Dan Harrison said Monday there were no conditions
attached to his company's donation.
   ``Thailand is an important country to us,'' Harrison said. ``But
the contribution was made for humanitarian reasons.''
   Harrision said UTC officials felt the amount of money was
``appropriate given the magnitude of the typhoon.'' He said the
giant aerospace and industrial concern also contributed to relief
efforts for victims of Hurricane Hugo and the earthquakes in San
Francisco and Armenia, but he said he didn't know how much it gave.
   The U.S. goverment donated $75,000 to the typhoon victims, the
Thai embassy said. GE did not contribute, spokesman Dwight Weber
said.
   UTC wanted to keep its donation quiet and ``didn't want any
publicity,'' said Promjit Boon-Lang, an information officer at the
Thai embassy.
   Franklin J. Parisi, UTC vice president for communications, said
the corporation makes donations ``all the time that we don't
announce.''
   LaRocque said the contribution, while legal, has an
``unpleasant, malodorus smell to it.''
   Industry analysts said UTC's contribution reflects its
recognition of the way business is done in many foreign countries.
   ``Business is done any way you can do it in Asia, any way you
can get it done,'' said Mark A. Bobbi, an analyst with Forecast
International in Newtown, Conn.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891219-0214 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-89 1305EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f AM-BusinessMirror Adv21   12-19 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Business Mirror, Adv 21,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv21</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release AMs Thursday, Dec. 21</HEAD>
<HEAD>Shakeout In The Automotive Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's car market is so suffused with
lookalike brands and models that competition increasingly will be
forced into pricing, says a professor who has studied the market
for three decades.
   He forecasts competitive pricing over the next few years ``like
we've never seen before'' with potentially severe damage to
products lines and even to entire manufacturing operations.
   ``There'll be a shakeout,'' says Professor Eugene Jennings of
Michigan State University, an adviser to top corporate executives
and an observer of the automotive industry whose opinions are
widely sought.
   ``We go into the 1990s with homogenization of design and style
clear across the board,'' said Jennings, who earlier attributed
some of General Motors' lost market share to a lack of
distinctiveness among its own brands.
   Now, he says, sameness pervades the whole industry to such an
extent that product differences are even too subtle for
advertising, being observable only after salesmen call attention to
them in the showroom.
   But getting buyers into the showrooms, particularly for cars
with little ``curb appeal,'' is more difficult than ever, Jennings
says, especially after two years in which sales were kept strong by
drawing from future markets.
   He says it is unlikely that any one manufacturer intended it
this way, but that they reacted in similar conservative ways to a
fear of overcapacity in the industry, rather than risk losing share
through unacceptable innovations.
   ``The consequences were too great if they guessed wrong,'' said
Jennings in an interview. ``New concepts would have presented too
much risk.'' And yet, he suggested, it might take the assumption of
such risk to make a breakthrough.
   The rare market situation already is reflected in advertising
where, he says, more and more money is spent simply to ``break
through the clutter and confusion,'' and images and themes
substitute for product distinctiveness.
   ``It's almost as if automobiles have become a commodity,'' said
Jennings, a business professor and author of many books about the
inner workings of corporations.
   The pricing problem could hardly be more serious, he says,
observing that prices are following the same conservative trend,
``a bit above or below the category average _ and be prepared to
make a deal.''
   While the sameness syndrome exists, he says, it will be
difficult for many car lines to sustain premium prices, since
customers can easily switch to the ``same'' car made by a different
manufacturer.
   Planning and development also are affected by the syndrome. Big
spending in this area always has been risky, if necessary, since a
new concept or radical style change might not be accepted.
   The failure of Ford's Edsel is a monument to that risk, and more
recently, says Jennings, photographs of General Motors' Saturn car,
a costly effort to rethink the entire production process, were
greeted by yawns.
   In the current market, where sales already have been
``borrowed'' from model years to come, and with large overcapacity
in manufacturing operations, the risk is magnified. ``No one can
afford to have an Edsel,'' says Jennings.
   While assumption of that risk might eventually be the only way
to dissolve the stalemate, Jennings feels for the time being
companies most likely will fight their battle on the pricing front.
   ``Prices will not hold at premium levels,'' he states.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv AMs Thursday, Dec. 21.</NOTE>
</DOC>
