<DOCNO> AP891219-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-89 1548EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-EthanolPlane 1stLd-Writethru   12-19 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ethanol Plane, 1st Ld-Writethru,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Atlantic Crossing Made By Ethanol Plane</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of pilot to Shauck, sted Schauck, in grafs
8, 9, 12, 16 and 18.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK McDOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It wasn't quite Lindbergh, but a Texas university
professor earned his footnote in aviation history Tuesday when he
completed the first trans-Atlantic flight in an ethanol-fueled
airplane.
   Max Shauck, a mathematics instructor at Baylor University in
Waco, Texas, landed at the small Toussus-le-Noble airport southwest
of Paris after a one-hour flight from Tours.
   He set out with Italian co-pilot Grazia Zanin from Waco on Sept.
15 in a light experimental aircraft that carried them through often
rough weather to Canada, the Azores, Portugal, Spain and finally
France.
   ``We feel we have proved that ethanol is a very reliable fuel,''
Shauck said. ``You can't get across the Atlantic on an unreliable
fuel.''
   Proving the merits of the relatively cheap, non-polluting
ethanol compared to standard fuel drove Shauck make the journey,
which he funded himself at more cost ``than I care to think about.''
   Ethanol is essentially an alcohol fuel made from vegetable
matter, usually corn in the United States and sugar beets in
Europe. Shauck, who also does air pollution research at Baylor,
says ethanol retails for about $1.20 per gallon in the United
States compared to $1.80 for high-octane aviation fuel.
   ``It produces more power, it burns cooler and there's a lot less
pollution,'' he said. ``But we had to go out of our way sometimes
to find it.''
   Indeed, Shauck and Zanin's flight log includes a hodgepodge of
small stopovers in North America chosen chiefly because ethanol
could be delivered there.
   These included Paducah, Ky.; Newark, Ohio; Hazelton, Pa.; and
Suffolk, N.Y. The plane also stopped at Shauck's hometown of
Mansfield, Ohio.
   In Canada, they stopped at Moncton and St. Pierre-et-Miquelon
before lifting off from St. John's, Newfoundland on Oct. 20 for
Flores in the Azore Islands, a 2,000-mile crossing made terrifying
by rain and thunderstorms.
   ``It's a long way over a lot of water when you're flying a
little plane looking for little islands,'' he said. ``We didn't
have sophisticated navigation equipment.''
   They waited in the Azores for nearly three weeks for a shipment
of ethanol to arrive before flying to Lisbon Nov. 10. Shauck, 54,
and Ms. Zanin, 33, made stops in Bilbao, Spain, and Bordeaux,
Rochet-Sur-Yon and Tours in France.
   Technically, they became the first people to cross the Atlantic
in an ethanol-fueled plane the minute they touched down in
Portugal, but the original plan they filed with American
authorities was from Suffolk County, N.Y., airport to Paris.
   The fiberglass aircraft, a sort of flying wing built by the
Velocity Corp. of Sebastian, Fla., featured elevators, normally
found on the tail, at the front of the airplane and a propellor
mounted on the back.
   The whole contraption weighs about 2,100 pounds and can reach a
top speed of 200 mph.
   Shauck resists comparison with American aviator Charles
Lindbergh, first man to cross the Atlantic in a flight from New
York to Le Bourget airport in Paris on May 31, 1927.
   ``He is a hero,'' Shauck said. ``Everything now is different
than it was in his day. I avoided going to Le Bourget because I
didn't want to be compared to him.''
   Shauck said he would take a commercial flight back to Texas, but
that the aircraft will make one more trip _ to Ms. Zanin's
hometown, Trieste.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891219-0225 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-89 1554EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-ResponsibleDrinking     12-19 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Responsible Drinking,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miller Launches $2 Million `Think When You Drink' Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYA L. WESLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Miller Brewing Co. will add a new medium this
week to its effort to teach consumers to drink responsibly when the
beermaker begins a $2 million television advertising campaign for
the holidays.
   The company has used the slogan ``Think When You Drink'' as a
tag line in its print advertisements and in taverns and liquor
stores, but this year's campaign will be the first time Miller has
used the slogan in a television campaign, spokeswoman Elizabeth
Conlisk said.
   ``We looked for a long time for the right tone and the right
message,'' Ms. Conlisk said. ``When we did it, we wanted to do it
right.''
   The television commercials were to start Thursday and run
through Dec. 31 and will have a ``warm and cozy feeling to them,''
Ms. Conlisk said.
   Rather than focusing on the problems irresponsible drinking can
cause, the commercials feature traditional American taverns.
   ``Taverns are places where people have gone for years to have
and beer and be with their friends,'' Ms. Conlisk said. ``These
commercials make people feel good about that.''
   The commercials include the message:
   ``The next time it's Miller Time for you, we'd like to ask you
to do one very simple thing. Be responsible. Think when you drink.''
   Milwaukee-based Miller, the No. 2. U.S. brewer, has sponsored
educational programs since 1984, based on what Ms. Conlisk called
the company's belief that education is the way to reduce alcohol
abuse.
   In the past, Miller has been criticized by anti-drinking
activists who claim the brewer has taken an inconsistent and
irresponsible approach toward selling its product.
   In March, for example, Miller was rebuked for running
advertisements in college newspapers' advertising supplements
intending to capitalize on the rollicking atmosphere of spring
vacation. Miller later withdrew and apologized for the ads, which
featured tips for men on how to `scam babes'' at the beach.
   In June, then-U.S. Surgeon General C. Everett Koop issued a set
of proposals that would ban alcohol advertisements on college
campuses and outlaw ads using celebrities who appeal to youths.
   Beer industry officials complained Koop's effort amounted to an
anti-alcohol campaign. They said while Koop's proposal went too
far, the industry as a whole was moving toward empashizing more
responsible drinking in an effort to discourage drunken driving.
   On New Year's Eve, Miller and its distributors will sponsor free
bus and taxi rides and designated-driver programs in many U.S.
cities to promote responsible drinking and safe driving, Ms.
Conlisk said.
   ``This is really a concerted effort nationwide to reinforce the
moderation theme,'' she said.
   Anheuser-Busch of St. Louis, Miller's top competitor, will use
the Budweiser Clydesdales in the brewers' long-running ``Know When
to Say When'' advertising campaign.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891219-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-19-89 1558EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-USX-Icahn     12-19 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-USX-Icahn,0277</SECOND>
<UNK>FTC Clears Icahn to Acquire Bigger Stake in USX Corp.</UNK>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal antitrust regulators have cleared
investor Carl C. Icahn to acquire a bigger stake in USX Corp., the
Federal Trade Commission said Tuesday.
   The agency said it had granted Icahn early termination of the
waiting period required under federal law to ensure that certain
mergers and acquisitions do not violate antitrust law.
   Icahn, known for his past corporate takeover attempts, also owns
Trans World Airlines Inc.
   In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission last
month, Icahn revealed he was seeking FTC permission to acquire at
least 25 percent of USX, a Pittsburgh-based steel and energy
company.
   FTC clearance for such an acquisition is required under the
Hart-Scott-Rodino Antitrust Improvements Act.
   The FTC announced Icahn's acquisition of USX was among the
transactions granted clearance, or early termination from the
waiting period. No other information was provided by the FTC.
   USX spokesman William Kessler declined to comment on Icahn's
filing.
   Icahn was in meetings Tuesday, his secretary said. He did not
immediately return calls seeking comment.
   Icahn's November SEC filing showed he owned nearly 34 million,
or 13.26 percent, of USX's outstanding shares of common stock. The
document said Icahn intended to acquire more than 15 percent of
USX's voting securities ``and, depending upon market conditions,
more than 25 percent'' of its voting securities.
   The filing said the acquisition was dependent on market
conditions and redemption or invalidation of a ``poison pill''
shareholder rights plan adopted by USX on Oct. 10 in an attempt to
ward off a hostile takeover.
</TEXT>
